Head of DPRK Delegation on Peace and Security on Korean Peninsula 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 9 (KCNA) -- Vice-Minister of the People's Armed Forces Kim Sang Ik who is heading a delegation of the DPRK clarified its view on the issue of preserving the regional peace and security centering around the Korean Peninsula in his speech made at the security policy meeting of the ASEAN Regional Forum on November 5.
 The basic factor of disturbing peace and stability in the Asian-Pacific region at present is a military threat based on unilateralism and high-handed acts, he said, adding that it is the Korean Peninsula where it is most strongly felt and it is, therefore, a most pressing issue in preserving the regional security to ensure peace on the peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He went on to say: The present U.S. administration listed the DPRK as part of an "axis of evil" and a target of its preemptive nuclear attack and adopted a policy for stifling it by force of arms. It has persistently resorted to the anti-DPRK hostile acts to bring down its system by mobilizing military forces and all other means. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Under this tense political and military situation surrounding the peninsula the DPRK is left with no other option but to increase self-defensive capability in every way in order to firmly defend the sovereignty of the country and the nation &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What is essential for completely removing the danger of war from the peninsula and ensuring the regional peace is to put an end to U.S. unilateralism and hegemony among other things, its hostile policy toward the DPRK and military threat, in particular. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. persistently follows its confrontational hostile policy toward the DPRK, in the future, too, from the viewpoint of escapism, this will only compel the latter to double its self-defensive military capability including nuclear deterrent. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean People's Army will as ever make every possible effort to avert a war on the Korean Peninsula and in the region and ensure lasting peace in reliance upon its self-reliant defence capability, he concluded.

Candlelight Rally Held for Abolition of NSL in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 9 (KCNA) -- A joint candlelight solidarity rally was reportedly held in front of the building of the "National Assembly" on Nov. 3 by more than 200 members of the People's Solidarity for Abolition of the "National Security Law", the Headquarters of the People's Movement for the Democratic Revision of the Law on Private Schools and Liquidation of the Corrupt History, the south Korean Federation of University Student Councils, the south Korean Council of Youth Organizations and other organizations in demand of the abolition of the NSL.
 It was attended by those on a sit-in strike in various parts of Seoul in demand of the NA passage of the bill on reform which reflects the stand of the progressive forces. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Speeches were made at the rally. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 O Jong Ryol, co-representative of the People's Solidarity, called on all the people to unite to pave the way for independence, reunification and democracy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Yu Son Hui, executive member of the Democratic Workers' Party, in a speech held that the NSL, an evil law dating back to the old era, should be abolished without fail. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Yun Hui Chan, director of the organizational department of the "National Teachers' Union" (Jongyojo), noted that preparations for joint lectures are brisk at schools across south Korea to demand the abrogation of the NSL with Jongyojo playing a major role in them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The rally was followed by an art performance given on theme of the abolition of the NSL. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants had a ceremony of lighting the candles bearing the words "Abolition of the NSL." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Prior to this, sit-in strikers of the People's Solidarity conducted information service and foot march in demand of the abolition of the evil law.

Declaration of 1,000 Peasants for Abolition of NSL in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 9 (KCNA) -- More than 1,300 members of the "National Federation of Peasants Associations" (Jonnong), the "National Federation of Women Peasants Associations", the south Korean Catholic Peasants Association and other organizations reportedly called a press conference in Youido, Seoul, on November 4 and made public a declaration of 1,000 peasants demanding the repeal of the "National Security Law".
 There Vice-Chairman of Jonnong So Jong Gil and Chairperson of its National Reunification Committee Han To Suk said the abolition of the evil law is inevitable, deploring that peasant activists were suppressed, charged with "enemy-benefiting," and agricultural exchange with the north was barred under the NSL. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They stated they would wage a fearless struggle for the repeal of the NSL and defense of food sovereignty with 30,000 peasants in attendance in front of Seoul Railway Station on November 13. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Permanent Representative of the Reunification Solidarity Han Sang Ryol said all the people should turn out in the fight for the abrogation of the evil law with a view to implementing the June 15 joint declaration and converting the confrontation of south Korea-U.S. alliance with the north into that of national alliance with the U.S. and make the next year, the 60th year after the division of the country, the first year of independent reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The declaration of 1,000 peasants read out at the press conference said the peasants would stand in the van of the fight for the abolition of the NSL, an evil law of the old era, and defense of food sovereignty and the righteous struggle to speed up national reunification.

Aerial Stunt "Twin Swinging" Awarded "Yellow Crane Gold Prize" 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 9 (KCNA) -- The aerial stunt "Twin Swinging" of the Pyongyang Circus was awarded "Yellow Crane Gold Prize", the first prize, and the "Balancing Stunt on the Rope" "Yellow Crane Silver Prize," the second prize, at the 6th Wuhan International Acrobatics Festival held in China from October 29 to November 5.
 Thirty-one excellent events were put on the stage of the festival which drew acrobats from 10 countries including the DPRK, China and Russia. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The mayor of the Wuhan City People's Government said after seeing the performance that Korean acrobatics was the world's first-class, adding that the key to this was the energetic leadership of Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The director of the Cultural Department of the city people's government said the aerial stunts performed by Korean acrobats at each festival were fascinating and they inspired people with courage and optimism. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The chairman of the Chinese Acrobats Association said the appearance of the Korean acrobats flying in the air was quite impressive, adding: We will strive to gain good results like them.

Winter Kimchi Prepared in Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 9 (KCNA) -- November is a season of preparing kimchi for winter in Korea.
 Kimchi has been favorite food of the Korean people since ancient times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kimchi is made in an industrial way in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea. But most of the families still like to make it by themselves. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Nowadays lorries loaded with vegetables are seen everywhere in streets and villages. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Women are sharing their experience in making tasty kimchi and neighbors helping each other in pickling vegetables and preparing spices. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 There are many kinds of kimchi. Typical of them are thong-kimchi made of whole cabbages, kkaktugi (radish kimchi heavily spiced with pepper and garlic), sokbak-kimchi (sliced cabbages and radishes seasoned with spices) and tongchimi (radishes pickled in salt water).
